I"a<p>I have been reading a lot on how consultants work: how they organize their time, how they manage stakeholders, how they present their work. And when it comes to consulting, Mckinsey is the gold standard.</p>

<p>Here are 3 of the best books on how they do their work.</p>

<ol>
  <li>
    <p>Learn about issue trees, MECE, and more in <a href="https://manassaloi.com/booksummaries/2016/04/20/mcKinsey-mind-ethan-paul.html">McKinsey Mind by Ethan M. Rasiel, Paul N. Friga</a>.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Learn about TEAM FOCUS model in The <a href="https://manassaloi.com/booksummaries/2016/01/27/mckinsey-engagement-friga.html">McKinsey Engagement by Paul N. Friga</a>.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Learn about the 47 principles mentioned in The <a href="https://manassaloi.com/booksummaries/2016/04/21/mcKinsey-edge-hattori.html">McKinsey Edge: Success Principles from the Worldâ€™s Most Powerful Consulting Firm by Shu Hattori</a>.</p>
  </li>
</ol>

<p>Other books I have read on Mckinsey and consulting in general: <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/16130157-the-firm">The firm</a> (history of Mckinsey), <a href="https://manassaloi.com/booksummaries/2016/05/29/secrets-of-consulting-gerald-weinberg.html">The Secrets of Consulting by Gerald M. Weinberg</a> (the orange test mentioned in the book literally changed my life)</p>

<p>Read about the Orange juice test here: <a href="https://intercom.com/blog/the-orange-juice-test/">Orange juice test</a></p>

<p>I am currently reading: <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/33206.The_Minto_Pyramid_Principle">The Pyramid Principle by Barbara Minto</a>. Here is a good summary of the book: <a href="https://medium.com/lessons-from-mckinsey/the-pyramid-principle-f0885dd3c5c7">The Pyramid Principle</a></p>

